Dialogue: 3,0:00:33.88,0:00:38.38,Callout,,0,0,0,,{\an8\pos(640,112)\fs21\c&H00988F8A&}// TONE DROPS. THIS IS THE MOMENT
Dialogue: 10,0:00:00.00,0:00:01.83,Caption,,0,0,0,,The number didn't fit.
Dialogue: 10,0:00:02.17,0:00:05.63,Caption,,0,0,0,,In that instant, the software did what\Nit was written
Dialogue: 10,0:00:05.63,0:00:09.10,Caption,,0,0,0,,to do when it hit an impossible\Nconversion. It flagged
Dialogue: 10,0:00:09.10,0:00:12.57,Caption,,0,0,0,,an error — and it shut the whole\Nnavigation unit
Dialogue: 10,0:00:12.57,0:00:12.91,Caption,,0,0,0,,down.
Dialogue: 10,0:00:13.25,0:00:17.33,Caption,,0,0,0,,The backup unit? It was running the\Nexact same code,
Dialogue: 10,0:00:17.33,0:00:21.40,Caption,,0,0,0,,reading the exact same too-large number.\NIt had failed a
Dialogue: 10,0:00:21.40,0:00:25.48,Caption,,0,0,0,,fraction of a second earlier, for\Nexactly the same reason.
Dialogue: 10,0:00:25.82,0:00:30.36,Caption,,0,0,0,,Two independent systems. One shared\Nflaw. Both gone. And
Dialogue: 10,0:00:30.36,0:00:33.39,Caption,,0,0,0,,the rocket was now flying blind.
Dialogue: 10,0:00:33.73,0:00:37.40,Caption,,0,0,0,,With both navigation units offline, the\Nfailed system did
Dialogue: 10,0:00:37.40,0:00:41.47,Caption,,0,0,0,,one last thing before it died. Instead\Nof sending flight
Dialogue: 10,0:00:41.47,0:00:45.55,Caption,,0,0,0,,data, it sent a diagnostic error code —\Nraw numbers,
Dialogue: 10,0:00:45.55,0:00:49.62,Caption,,0,0,0,,meant for engineers on the ground, never\Nmeant for the
Dialogue: 10,0:00:49.62,0:00:50.44,Caption,,0,0,0,,flight computer.
